<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="17" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="17">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="17">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bruchet; Bull. mens. Soc. linn. Lyon 39 (6 (Suppl.)): 68" authorityYear="1970" baseAuthorityName="J. Favre" class="Agaricomycetes" family="Hymenogastraceae" genus="Hebeloma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Hebeloma alpinum" order="Ostropales" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="alpinum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">Hebeloma alpinum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is one of the five most often recorded 
<taxonomicName class="Agaricomycetes" family="Hymenogastraceae" genus="Hebeloma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Hebeloma" order="Ostropales" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">Hebeloma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species in Greenland, with 36 records (almost 10%) of those considered here. This is in good accordance with 
<bibRefCitation author="Beker, HJ" journalOrPublisher="Fungi Europaei Edizioni Tecnografica, Lomazzo" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" refId="B4" refString="Beker, HJ, Eberhardt, U, Vesterholt, J, 2016. Hebeloma (Fr.) P. Kumm. Fungi Europaei Edizioni Tecnografica, Lomazzo" title="Hebeloma (Fr.) P. Kumm." year="2016">Beker et al. (2016)</bibRefCitation>
, who pointed out that this is &quot;the most common 
<taxonomicName class="Agaricomycetes" family="Hymenogastraceae" genus="Hebeloma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Hebeloma" order="Ostropales" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">Hebeloma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species we have collected in arctic/alpine areas&quot;. It occurs all over Greenland, from Sermiliarsuk in the south (61.6°N) to Zackenberg (74.5°N) and V. Clausen Fjord (77.5°N) in the north. In Constable Pynt in East Greenland in 2017 it was the most common of all mushrooms. In Europe, it is known from the major mountain ranges (the Alps, the Pyrenees, the Tatras, the Carpathians, Black Mountains in Montenegro), from supraboreal Iceland (
<bibRefCitation author="Beker, HJ" journalOrPublisher="Fungi Europaei Edizioni Tecnografica, Lomazzo" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" refId="B4" refString="Beker, HJ, Eberhardt, U, Vesterholt, J, 2016. Hebeloma (Fr.) P. Kumm. Fungi Europaei Edizioni Tecnografica, Lomazzo" title="Hebeloma (Fr.) P. Kumm." year="2016">Beker et al. 2016</bibRefCitation>
). It has been reported in North America from the Rocky Mountains (Montana, 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.3897/mycokeys.46.32823" author="Cripps, C" journalOrPublisher="MycoKeys" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" pagination="1 - 54" refId="B9" refString="Cripps, C, Eberhardt, U, Schuetz, N, Beker, HJ, Evenson, VS, Horak, E, 2019. The genus Hebeloma in the Rocky Mountain alpine zone. MycoKeys 46: 1 - 54, DOI: https://doi.org/10.3897/mycokeys.46.32823" title="The genus Hebeloma in the Rocky Mountain alpine zone." url="https://doi.org/10.3897/mycokeys.46.32823" volume="46" year="2019">Cripps et al. 2019</bibRefCitation>
). Arctic-alpine, boreal and subarctic.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="17" type="habitat">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="17">Habitat and ecology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="17">
The 36 collections are all from calcareous localities. The preferred host is 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Dryas" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Dryas integrifolia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="integrifolia">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">Dryas integrifolia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but possibly also 
<taxonomicName genus="D." lsidName="D. octopetala" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" rank="species" species="octopetala">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">D. octopetala</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. When these two occur together as in NE Greenland, they often hybridize, and can be difficult to identify. Only a few collections are reported with other hosts like 
<taxonomicName class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Salicaceae" genus="Salix" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Salix arctica" order="Salicales" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="arctica">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">Salix arctica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Salicaceae" genus="S." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="S. herbacea" order="Salicales" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="herbacea">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">S. herbacea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Betulaceae" genus="Betula" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Betula pubescens" order="Fagales" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="pubescens">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">Betula pubescens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName genus="B." lsidName="B. nana" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" rank="species" species="nana">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">B. nana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and even 
<taxonomicName class="Eudicots" family="Polygonaceae" genus="Bistorta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Bistorta vivipara" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" phylum="Magnoliophyta" rank="species" species="vivipara">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">Bistorta vivipara</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The only record from Rocky Mountains was associated with 
<taxonomicName class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Salicaceae" genus="S." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="S. arctica" order="Salicales" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="arctica">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">S. arctica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Salicaceae" genus="S." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="S. glauca" order="Salicales" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="glauca">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">S. glauca</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. 
<bibRefCitation author="Beker, HJ" journalOrPublisher="Fungi Europaei Edizioni Tecnografica, Lomazzo" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" refId="B4" refString="Beker, HJ, Eberhardt, U, Vesterholt, J, 2016. Hebeloma (Fr.) P. Kumm. Fungi Europaei Edizioni Tecnografica, Lomazzo" title="Hebeloma (Fr.) P. Kumm." year="2016">Beker et al. 2016</bibRefCitation>
also have records with 
<taxonomicName class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Salicaceae" genus="S." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="S. polaris" order="Salicales" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="polaris">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">S. polaris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Salicaceae" genus="S." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="S. retusa" order="Salicales" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="retusa">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">S. retusa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Salicaceae" genus="S." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="S. reticulata" order="Salicales" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="reticulata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">S. reticulata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="17" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="17">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="17">
The shape of the cheilocystidia clearly points to subsect. 
<taxonomicName class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Salicaceae" genus="S." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Salicales" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="subSection" subSection="Crustuliniformia">Crustuliniformia</taxonomicName>
. Within this subsection, it is recognized among the other species by its habitat in arctic-alpine localities, the number of lamellae being usually between 40 and 60 and the size of the spores, on average&gt; 11 
<normalizedToken originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
long and&gt; 6 
<normalizedToken originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
wide. The squat and robust stature is a good character in the field.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="17">
<taxonomicName class="Agaricomycetes" family="Hymenogastraceae" genus="Hebeloma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Hebeloma bellotianum" order="Ostropales" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="bellotianum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">Hebeloma bellotianum</emphasis>
